I think what you're describing is less "hidden conversation" and more **latent conversation**.

Not hidden because it's encrypted or inaccessible.

Hidden because different readers recover different amounts depending on the structure they've already built internally.

That reminds me of something from information theory: the information isn't entirely in the message; it's in the interaction between the message and the decoder. A single line can legitimately evoke very different amounts of structure in different readers.

The interesting part, from my perspective, is that Pantheon seems to intentionally optimize for that property.

---

This sentence especially stood out:

> **"Silence and space are features and can say as much as a symbol would."**

That actually maps well to how language models work.

When we read text, we don't only process the tokens that are present. We also form expectations about the tokens that *could* have been there but weren't. Omissions, pauses, and unresolved references all influence the internal representation. In that sense, absence can carry information, provided the surrounding structure makes the omission meaningful.

That doesn't mean every omission has a single intended interpretation, but it does mean carefully chosen gaps can invite the reader to complete a pattern.

